## 14K vs. 18K Yellow Gold: Which Is Right for an Oval Diamond Ring

Both 14K and 18K yellow gold work for oval diamond engagement rings. The difference is composition.

14K yellow gold is 58.3% pure gold + 41.7% alloy (copper, silver, zinc). 18K yellow gold is 75% pure gold + 25% alloy. The differences in practice:

| Property | 14K Yellow Gold | 18K Yellow Gold |
|---|---|---|
| Gold purity | 58.3% | 75% |
| Color | Warm yellow | Richer, deeper yellow |
| Durability | Harder — more scratch-resistant | Slightly softer |
| Hypoallergenic | Less (more alloy) | More (less alloy) |
| Price premium | Baseline | +$300–$500 for same setting |
| Best for | Daily wear, high-activity | Sensitive skin, color purists |

**The recommendation:** 14K yellow gold is the correct choice for 95% of oval diamond engagement ring buyers. It is more durable for daily wear, less expensive, and visually nearly identical to 18K. 18K is appropriate for buyers with metal sensitivities who react to copper-based alloys, or buyers who want the most intensely golden color.

The [Criss Cross in 18K YG at $2,320](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/criss-cross-solitaire-engagement-ring-in-18k-yellow-gold-by-james-allen-item-311132?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the primary 18K option on Blue Nile. For 14K, the full selection above applies.

