## Yellow Gold Oval Diamond Solitaire: The Color Grade Rule

This decision framework applies to every yellow gold oval diamond ring purchase:

**In 14K yellow gold:** G color is the sweet spot. Near-colorless with no visible warmth on the finger in any lighting condition. H color is acceptable and reads as colorless in most lighting — saves $2,700–$3,200 at 2ct. I color shows slightly warm in outdoor bright light — not recommended.

**In 18K yellow gold:** H color is the sweet spot. The deeper yellow tone of 18K makes even I color read acceptably warm, so buyers gain an additional step in savings. G is unnecessary in 18K — the color is absorbed by the richer gold tone.

**Clarity minimum:** VS1 for guaranteed eye-clean appearance at any carat weight under 3ct. VS2 is acceptable with video review. SI1 is too risky in ovals — inclusions that are borderline in round diamonds read more clearly through the oval's wider table.

**GIA vs. IGI for natural stones:** Buy GIA-certified natural oval diamonds only. IGI grades natural stones more generously than GIA — an IGI G-VS2 natural oval may actually be H-SI1 in GIA standards. For lab-grown diamonds, IGI is the appropriate certification.

